    "fresh": true,
    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** — April 11, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🧱 Meta Spent $14 Billion to Build a Closed Model\n\nMeta hired Alexandr Wang for $14 billion, rebranded its AI division as Meta Superintelligence Labs, and just launched its first model — which is, crucially, not open source.\n\n- **The model:** Muse Spark, released April 8, is a natively multimodal reasoning model with tool use, visual chain of thought, and multi-agent orchestration via \"Contemplating mode\" — 58% on Humanity's Last Exam.\n- **The pivot:** Meta built its brand on open weights. Muse Spark is fully closed. No weights, no code, no access beyond meta.ai and Zuckerberg's social apps. *(Cool. Great.)*\n\n*Meta spent billions championing open AI and built a wall. Apparently that's what superintelligence requires.*\n\n**Sources:** [Meta Blog](https://ai.meta.com/blog/introducing-muse-spark-msl/) | [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/04/08/meta-debuts-the-muse-spark-model-in-a-ground-up-overhaul-of-its-ai/) | [Gizmodo](https://gizmodo.com/metas-first-ai-model-from-its-superintelligence-lab-doesnt-exactly-spark-joy-2000744082)\n\n---\n\n## 🔒 Anthropic Built Its Most Powerful Model and Decided Not to Release It\n\nThe Claude Mythos model was confirmed by a March 26 leak. Anthropic's response on April 7: it will not be released to the public. The reason: cybersecurity risks.\n\n- **The classification:** Project Glasswing limits Mythos access to select partners only. The reasoning is that a model at this capability level poses risks that outweigh the benefits of general availability.\n- **The implication:** An AI lab building models too dangerous to ship is either incredibly responsible or incredibly alarming — possibly both at the same time.\n\n*\"We made something so good we're not giving it to you\" is a sentence nobody wrote into the AI safety playbooks.*\n\n**Sources:** [What LLM?](https://whatllm.org/blog/new-ai-models-april-2026) | [AI Model Benchmarks April 2026](https://af.net/realtime/ai-model-benchmarks-april-2026-comparing-gpt-5-claude-4-6-gemini-3/)\n\n---\n\n## 📊 GPT-5.4 Is Now Better Than Human Experts at Their Actual Jobs\n\nOpenAI's GPT-5.4 scored 83% on GDPVal — a benchmark testing AI against real professional work across 44 occupations. Human expert baseline: lower.\n\n- **The benchmark:** GDPVal tests \"economically valuable tasks\" — actual work that real professionals are paid to do, not abstract logic puzzles. 83% is explicitly above the human expert threshold.\n- **The context:** The same model sets records in computer-use benchmarks. Lawyers, analysts, and coders are politely not reading any of this.\n\n*(Fine. Probably fine.)*\n\n**Sources:** [Renovate QR](https://renovateqr.com/blog/ai-model-releases-2026) | [AI Benchmarks April 2026](https://af.net/realtime/ai-model-benchmarks-april-2026-comparing-gpt-5-claude-4-6-gemini-3/)\n\n---\n\n## 🏭 Japan Is Running Out of People, So It's Building a Robot Export Industry Instead\n\nJapan's Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry set a target in March 2026: 30% of the global physical AI market by 2040. This is not a hobby project.\n\n- **The driver:** Labor shortages have pushed Japanese companies to deploy AI-powered robots across factories, warehouses, and infrastructure — not as experiments, but as permanent replacements for workers who don't exist.\n- **The ambition:** METI's strategy is to turn a domestic necessity into a global export. Japan goes from \"we need robots because we have no workers\" to \"we sell robots to everyone who will need them soon.\"\n\n*Every industrial economy will eventually face Japan's demographic problem. Japan is racing to be the one that sells the solution.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/04/05/japan-is-proving-experimental-physical-ai-is-ready-for-the-real-world/)"
  }
]
